Describes the full compilation pipeline from `dict.steno` to the four `out/` artifacts (`plain-ts.json`, `smart-ts.json`, `vim-snippets.json`, `snippets.json`), naming the exact pass order, module dependency direction, error-type-per-pass taxonomy, and the shared editor model. This is the authoritative cross-reference for how `crates/steno/src/{parse,expand,render,snippet.rs,blocks.rs,editor,error.rs}` fit together — read it before restructuring any pass boundary or changing what a pass is allowed to emit.

Key facts an editor must not violate: the pipeline is Entry → (Pass A: `expand/counts.rs`) → ExpandedEntry → (Pass B: `expand/append.rs`+`types.rs`) → TypedEntry → (line-flag: `expand/lineflag.rs`) → TypedEntry, then branches to `render/plain.rs`, `render/smart.rs`, `snippet.rs`. `expand_dict` in `expand/mod.rs` runs Pass A, Pass B, and line-flag as one call, and — critically — also runs `fix_family_terminals` (`expand/family.rs`) immediately after Pass A/B, *before* line-flag; this whole-batch post-pass corrects `terminal` flags that `expand_types_one` cannot know per-entry (a "family root" stroke that happens to be a `/`-prefix of a separately authored later entry must be forced non-terminal). After Pass A, no `Repeat`/`Dcount`/`Computed` chunks may survive — a renderer or later pass seeing one is a bug, not user error.

The doc states the module dependency direction as an intent invariant: `stroke ← parse ← expand ← {editor, render, snippet, blocks}`, with `json_out` as a leaf used only at emission — no back-edges allowed. It documents the `TypedEntry.terminal` distinction (complete construct vs. type-append intermediate) as load-bearing for `snippet.rs`: only terminal entries may be handed to the nvim plugin as real snippets (`{^}@@…@@{^}` sentinel-wrapped), because a non-terminal is always later superseded by a longer chord and Plover corrects it via backspace-count, which would desync if the nvim plugin had already rewritten that text.

It also specifies the `Behaviors` preset table (`PLAIN`/`SMART`/`SMART_INDENT` via `auto_close`/`type_over`/`auto_indent` flags) that parameterizes the shared `editor/` model (`interpret`, `movement_events`, `serialize`) — changing renderer behavior means changing the right preset, not hardcoding profile-specific logic in `render/`. And it enumerates the five error types (`StenoError`, `StrokeError`, `ExpandError`, `RenderError`, `SnippetError`) and which pass raises each, with `ExpandError: From<StrokeError>` — a new pass introducing failures should reuse or extend this taxonomy rather than panic or add an ad hoc error type.